In[1]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
In[2]:
N = 100_000
sigma = 3  # 
alpha = np.random.beta(a=2, b=5, size=N)
p, q = 1, 1
I = np.random.lognormal(size=N)
X = I/q/(p/q + ((1-alpha)/alpha*p/q)**sigma)
Y = (I - p*X)/q
In[4]:
print(f'Average X is {X.mean()} and Average log(X) is {np.log(X.mean())}')

Average X is 0.26047900024139586 and Average log(X) is -1.3452330343149317
In[5]:
print(f'Average Y is {Y.mean()} and Average log(Y) is {np.log(Y.mean())}')

Average Y is 1.3768265381173217 and Average log(Y) is 0.3197812409453793
In[6]:
sns.displot(x=np.log(X), kind="kde", color='r')
plt.xlabel('log(X)');
In[7]:
sns.displot(x=X, kind="kde", color='r')
plt.xlabel('X');
In[8]:
sns.displot(x=np.log(Y), kind="kde", color='r')
plt.xlabel('log(Y)');
In[9]:
sns.displot(x=Y, kind="kde", color='r')
plt.xlabel('Y');
